div.div: Flot. Smpl. 2 (5576), >4mm, diagnostics only. A large unit of light to medium brown bone with <5% burning and less digestion and gnawing than in many west fill units. The fragment size is relatively small with few pieces larger then 3 cm, but there are not many very small crumbles. Although slightly mixed in colour the material is only occasionally rolled or abraded. All parts of the skeleton are present in the 03 category including the axial skeleton. However, feet dominate. There is a range of ages including infantile to adult. There are 3 hyoid fragments, one very young, indicating excellent preservation - so the body part distribution is not a preservation issue. There are three very young horn cores, one goat, one sheep and one probably sheep. Additionally there are 4 03 vertebra, that appear to have been articulated in the ground. The material is largely post-butchery waste with some post-consumption all worked over by dogs. There are many individuals involved and the material is quite dense Taxa include sheep, goat, cattle, dog, badger, deer and one human tarsal. Only the caprids are represented by more than a few bones. The unit looks midden like - more like the neolithic mound midden/fill. It is interesting that there is less digestion in this midden then in fill. It is certainly well preserved and very undisturbed. There are two small bone points made on metapodials with squared (abraded) ends. These were pulled for further study. NB: Originally one small bag was received and processed. Subsequently most of the unit showed up. The FUD was rewritten to reflect the whole unit, but the recording numbers skip all over the place and many scrap categories are in several separate records NBB: Yet more stuff showed up. Recording is all over the place, but the FUD is not substantially changed. The microfauna and fish bone were pulled for further study including one fish that looks like the same as the common neolithic fish (different and smaller than most of the west fish). In the final bag there was an almost complete mole rat skull. it has been sent to microfauna instead of ritually destroyed. The flot sample is mainly 1 cm fragments of light, medium and grey bone. There is about 5-8 % burning and no digestion. Edges are sharp and unabraded and there is no trample polish. Last Number = 414

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
